## 🛠️ Phase 1 – Elite DSA + Full System Design + Core Mastery  
**(Months 1–18 – Third Year & Beyond)**

### 1. Elite DSA – Company & Pattern Mastery
**Focus:** Hard patterns, company-tagged marathons, contest-level speed & accuracy

**Detailed Monthly Breakdown**

**Months 1–4 – Graphs & DP Mastery**
- Graphs: Dijkstra with heap, Bellman-Ford negative cycles, Floyd-Warshall all pairs, MST Kruskal/Prim + applications, SCC (Kosaraju/Tarjan), bridges & articulation points
- DP advanced: 2D/3D DP, bitmask DP (TSP, assignment), digit DP, DP on trees, DP optimization (convex hull, divide & conquer)
- Trie & Advanced String: Suffix array intro, KMP/Z-algo applications, longest palindromic substring variants

**Months 5–8 – Segment Tree, Fenwick, Advanced Structures**
- Segment Tree (range min/max/query/update, lazy propagation)
- Fenwick Tree / Binary Indexed Tree (range sum, inversion count)
- Disjoint Set Union (DSU) with path compression + rank + rollback
- Hard Greedy + Binary Search on Answer (minimize max, maximize min)

**Months 9–12 – Hard Backtracking, Heaps, Trees**
- Hard backtracking with pruning (N-Queens variants, sudoku optimizer, cryptarithmetic)
- Advanced Heaps (median in stream, sliding window median, task scheduler III)
- Advanced Trees: Heavy-Light Decomposition intro, Centroid Decomposition, Tree flattening

**Months 13–18 – Company-Specific + Contest Domination**
- Company marathons: Amazon → Google → Microsoft → Atlassian → Flipkart → Goldman tagged hard
- Weekly/biweekly LeetCode contests + virtual contests
- Codeforces rounds (aim Expert by end)
- Optimization tricks: bit manipulation, math, geometry basics

**Quantitative Targets**
- Total solved: 1200–2000+
- Medium: 700–1100
- Hard: 400–600+
- LeetCode: 400+ hard, Knight/Guardian track
- Contest rating: LeetCode 1600–2000+, Codeforces Specialist–Expert

**Elite Resources**
- Striver A2Z DSA Sheet + hard playlists
- Love Babbar company-specific lists
- takeUforward advanced series
- CP-Algorithms.com + USACO Guide
- NeetCode All + LeetCode hard frequency

### 2. System Design – Full Readiness
**Low-Level Design (LLD / OOP Design) – Must Master**
- Design: Parking Lot, Elevator System, Chess Game, Vending Machine, Ride-Sharing (Uber-like entities), Library Management, Snake & Ladder
- Advanced patterns: Strategy, Observer, Decorator, Command, State, Visitor, Flyweight
- SOLID + GRASP principles applied in code

**High-Level Design (HLD / Distributed Systems)**
- Design: TinyURL, Instagram Feed, WhatsApp Group Chat, Uber Backend, Netflix Recommendation, Twitter Timeline, Amazon Order System
- Core concepts:  
  - Load Balancing (round-robin, least connection, consistent hashing)  
  - Caching (Redis, Memcached, cache invalidation strategies)  
  - Databases (sharding, replication, CAP theorem, consistency models)  
  - Message Queues (Kafka, RabbitMQ, SQS – pub/sub vs queue)  
  - Microservices vs Monolith (pros/cons, API Gateway, service discovery)  
  - Rate Limiting, Circuit Breaker, Bulkhead

**Resources**
- Grokking the System Design Interview (Educative)
- ByteByteGo YouTube + Alex Xu books
- System Design Primer GitHub repo
- Striver / Gaurav Sen system design playlist
- Designing Data-Intensive Applications (select chapters)

### 3. Core Subjects – Expert Interview Level
**OOP & Design**
- Design complete systems using OOP principles + patterns

**DBMS Expert**
- Query optimization, execution plans, indexing strategies
- Sharding vs partitioning, NoSQL design trade-offs
- ACID vs BASE, eventual consistency patterns

**OS Expert**
- Linux process model (fork/exec/wait), signals, threads implementation
- Kernel modules basics, scheduling in Linux (CFS)
- File system internals (ext4, inodes)

**CN Expert**
- TLS 1.3 handshake deep, WebSockets vs SSE vs long polling
- CDN architecture, DNSSEC basics
- Load balancing types + sticky sessions + health checks

